@rhatdan not really.  This looks like it's a result of the way `docker-daemon` handles writing images to the daemon: by creating an [image tarball](https://docs.docker.com/engine/api/v1.24/#image-tarball-format) and uploading it to the daemon using [its `/images/load` endpoint](https://docs.docker.com/engine/api/v1.40/#operation/ImageLoad).

Looking at [the API docs](https://docs.docker.com/engine/api/latest/), I don't see an efficient way of checking which layers the daemon already has, which we'd probably need to be able to do in order to be able to figure out which layers we could omit from the image tarball that we generate for uploading.

Whether or not we can get enough information to be able to confidently skip copying layers is going to vary from transport to transport.
